Title: DISTRICT ZERO
Credit: Episode 01 — "The Sealed City"
Author: [Author]
Draft date: 2026-04-30
Contact: [Contact]


FADE IN:


EXT. DISTRICT ZERO OUTER WALL — NIGHT

Black water. A drowned city skyline — each tower a specific
shape against the dark. Not a blur. A graveyard of architecture.

A searchbeam sweeps. Cold, mechanical, 4-second arcs.
It finds nothing. It always finds nothing.

The beam crosses the water surface. The reflection holds for
a moment, then the dark swallows it.

This world is already finished. Nobody announced it.


INT. LOWER TRANSIT STACK — SERVICE CORRIDOR — NIGHT

A narrow maintenance corridor, 2.2 metres wide, running to
infinity. Riveted steel walls. Cable bundles like arteries.
A single cage lamp at the far vanishing point — the only
light source. Everything else: shadow.

NARA VOSS (late 20s, dark hair pulled back, utility jacket
worn to the body) sprints toward camera. Left leg forward.
Wrist display flashing amber below her chin.

She's not panicked. She runs here. She knows this floor.

She stops.

The wrist display: a sealed route blinks — once, twice —
then disappears. Her thumb hovers. Then captures it.

She looks at what she's just found.

She knows immediately.

At the mouth of an unmapped access corridor, she pauses.
One hand on the wall edge. Looks into the dark ahead.

Then she steps through.


INT. PRESSURE VALVE CHAMBER — NIGHT

Cathedral scale. Ceiling lost in darkness fifteen metres up.
Wall-to-wall cast-iron manifolds. Flanged pipes in arrays.
An alarm strobe cycles — white pulse every two seconds,
slamming hard shadows across metal surfaces.

NARA puts both hands on a valve wheel. Feet braced. Body
weight forward. She turns against pressure. The machinery
dwarfs her — she is ten percent of the frame.

THE ALARM CUTS. Silence lands like a physical weight.

Workers in coveralls look up. One steps forward.

WORKER
You just saved half the block.

NARA
Who signed the last maintenance map update?

WORKER
Central Authority. Same as always.

Nara looks at the hidden route on her wrist display.
The amber glow catches her face from below.

The maintenance error was not an error.


INT. VOSS APARTMENT — LOWER STACK — LATE NIGHT

Cramped. Peeling paint over exposed concrete. A single
practical lamp — amber, cloth-shade — the only warmth
in the frame. Neon from outside bleeding cold through
the condensation-fogged window.

NARA places the captured map route on the table between them.

ELIAN VOSS (early 50s, heavy weathered face, silver streak
above the right temple) sees it.

He freezes.

His jaw tightens. He looks at the wall — not at her.
He has always known this moment would come.

NARA
This showed up inside a live stack map and then vanished.

ELIAN
Forget it.

NARA
Then why are you scared of a corridor?

A long beat. The desk lamp. The neon outside. The silence.

ELIAN
Because in this city, hidden doors are never just doors.


INT. CIVIC ATRIUM — DISTRICT ZERO CENTRAL CORE — MORNING

Vast. Polished marble floor eighty metres across. A glass
ceiling diffusing flat grey morning sky. Giant propaganda
screens on the east wall — DIRECTOR HALDEN ROOK's face
twelve metres tall.

Hundreds of citizens move below in patterns that suggest
choreography, not freedom.

On a glass-and-steel balcony above, COMMANDER SARIN VALE
(late 40s, black tactical uniform, cold grey-blue eyes)
receives a tablet from an AIDE.

He reads it. His expression does not change.

VALE
Put her under passive watch.

AIDE
Detain?

Vale is already looking back at the atrium floor.

VALE
No. If she found one door, I want to know whether
she can find the next.

He doesn't look at the aide when he says it. The aide
hesitates. Vale has already stopped listening.


INT. BLACK MARKET EXCHANGE — VENTILATION SUBLEVEL — DAY

Underground. Dense. Vendor stalls from scavenged server
racks. Neon signs — cyan and amber — at two-metre height.
Forty people as background, specific details, not a crowd blur.

MIRA SOL (mid-30s, black hair cropped military-close,
worn olive canvas vest) bends over a display spread.

She studies Nara's stolen map. Lays it over archived
infrastructure data. Her finger traces a route.

A new path appears on the display — leading toward the
outer wall. Mira doesn't smile. She calculates.

MIRA
This isn't erased infrastructure. It's masked infrastructure.

NARA
Can you open it?

Mira looks at her. A long beat. Both calculating the
other's risk. Both reaching the same conclusion at
the same speed.

MIRA
Probably. The better question is whether you survive
after I do.


INT. SECURITY OPERATIONS CENTER — DAY

A wall of twelve monitors — cold cyan glow. Analysts at
stations facing the display wall. VALE stands two metres
back, arms behind his back. Near-silhouette against the
cold window behind.

A movement signature converges on the outer sectors.
Analysts update coordinates without speaking.

Vale does not give the order to intercept.

VALE
If she reaches the gate, I want to know what she thinks
she saw.

A pause. His eyes remain on the display.

VALE (CONT'D)
Don't stop her.


INT. SEALED SERVICE SPINE — NIGHT

Symmetrical. Extreme vanishing-point perspective. Wooden
plank walls. Corroded iron pipe bundles along the floor.
Two narrow-gauge tracks in dust-covered concrete.

Emergency floor-level fluorescent strips recede into fog.
Green-tinted. Near-absolute darkness ahead.

NARA moves through first, one hand on the pipe bundle.
MIRA three steps behind. Both without hesitation.
They have committed.

At an ancient relay panel on the left wall, Mira stops.
Powers it up. Capacitor whine. Relay clicks. Amber gauges
light one by one.

The system identifies an external containment access route.

NARA
Containment from what?

Mira reads the identifier. Her expression shifts — this
is not what she expected.

She unlocks the gate. A deep mechanical clunk.


INT. EXTERNAL OBSERVATION CHAMBER — CONTINUOUS

Industrial scale. Hydraulic cylinders. Corroded copper
piping with verdigris. A bank of mechanical shutters
across the outer wall — steel slats, motorised, beginning
to open.

Red alarm ceiling strip floods the chamber. Interior vs
exterior: warm red against the cold grey-blue growing
through the opening shutters.

Nara and Mira are silhouetted against the gap.

Organised lights in the far distance. Grid. Moving
vehicles. A city that was declared dead.

NARA
They lied.

She says it very quietly. Like a diagnosis.

She sees the industrial pumps in the wall structure —
pipes leading down through the floor into the lower
sectors. The infrastructure is already there.

The second blow lands harder than the first.

MIRA
We need to go. Now.

Mira pulls her by the arm. Nara takes one last look
at the lights before being pulled back into the tunnel.

A silent alarm floods the chamber red.


INT. SERVICE SPINE — CONTINUOUS

Security shutters slam down the corridor behind them —
sequential, one every second, getting closer.

BOTH sprint at full speed. Ducking under the last shutter.

Armed units pour into the shaft entrance at the far end.
Weapon lights sweep through dust and smoke.

VALE (V.O.)
Nara Voss. Stop running. The truth is not what you
think it is.

Mira finds a side duct. Reaches in. One foot inside.
She looks back once.

Then she disappears. No goodbye. Tactical.

Nara dives through a closing blast door. The narrowing
gap. Barely. The door slams.

Weapon lights reach the door surface.

Too late.


INT. VOSS APARTMENT — PRE-DAWN

Dark. The desk lamp is off. The only light: cold pre-dawn
blue from the small window — a thin horizontal bar across
the floor.

NARA enters — wet, shaken, changed. Closes the door
quietly. She is carrying something enormous and trying
not to show it.

ELIAN has been awake. Waiting. He sees her face.

He doesn't speak. He doesn't need to.

The secret he has carried for years has just walked
through the door.

NARA
There are people outside the wall. And they're
dumping poison into the lower sectors.

ELIAN
I know.

She recoils — not physically. Internally.

ELIAN (CONT'D)
I helped design part of the flow control system.

The truth lands between them. She doesn't look away.

ELIAN (CONT'D)
If they take me, this is the only thing that proves
the system was built this way.

He produces an encrypted drive from inside his jacket.
His hands are not steady. This is the only act of
courage he has left.

ELIAN (CONT'D)
Go to the freight tunnels. Find the relay called
Lantern. Ask for Mira Sol. Open the city.

She takes the drive. Holds it.

This is not what she wanted from him.

At the door: a thin line of corridor light under the gap.
Then a shadow. Then a second shadow.

Tactical boots. Heavy. Multiple pairs. Closing distance.

ELIAN
Open the city.

The door detonates inward.

                                          SMASH CUT TO BLACK.


THE END OF EPISODE 1
